## Yes! Async Variants Accept Executor Too!

This is actually the **most granular control** you can get.

---

## How it works

```java
ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id), vExec)  // virtual thread
    .thenApplyAsync(user -> enrichUser(user), vExec)        // virtual thread
    .thenAcceptAsync(user -> saveToDb(user), vExec)         // virtual thread
    .exceptionally(ex -> null);
```

Every stage runs on a **separate virtual thread**.

---

## Sync vs Async Variants — Key Difference

```java
ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id), vExec)

    // thenApply — runs on SAME thread that completed previous stage
    .thenApply(user -> transform(user))

    // thenApplyAsync (no executor) — hands off to ForkJoinPool
    .thenApplyAsync(user -> transform(user))

    // thenApplyAsync (with vExec) — hands off to a NEW virtual thread ✅
    .thenApplyAsync(user -> transform(user), vExec);
```

---

## When to pass vExec to async variants?

```java
ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id), vExec)

    // ✅ Pass vExec — this stage does blocking I/O
    .thenApplyAsync(user -> callAnotherAPI(user), vExec)

    // ✅ No executor needed — pure CPU transformation, no blocking
    .thenApply(data -> parseJson(data))

    // ✅ Pass vExec — saving to DB is blocking
    .thenAcceptAsync(data -> saveToDb(data), vExec);
```

---

## The Complete Picture

| Variant | Runs On | Pass vExec? |
|---|---|---|
| `.thenApply()` | Same thread as previous stage | N/A |
| `.thenApplyAsync()` | ForkJoinPool (default) | ❌ not needed for CPU work |
| `.thenApplyAsync(fn, vExec)` | New virtual thread | ✅ for blocking I/O stages |

---

## Bottom Line

> You **can and should** pass `vExec` to async variants **per stage** based on what that stage does.
> This gives you **fine-grained control** — blocking stages get virtual threads, CPU stages stay on ForkJoinPool.
> No need to blindly pass `vExec` everywhere — only where **blocking I/O** happens.
